poem:
The Sandwroth

'Twas sandling, and the whirry grains
Did skir and skamble o'er the flats;
The bluster-brine with sash and strains
Skried drift and dimpled scurfy spats.

Beware the Sandwroth, my son!
Beware the Gritter-snout and Graw;
The whorl-wind's jaws, the grit-grim tongue,
That grinds the seams and gnaws the maw.

He took his oiled shank in hand;
Long time he watched the dune-rows swell;
He braced his boot on shingle-stand
And listened to the sandbell's knell.

Then came the Sandwroth, all swath and sweep,
A flung and flittered sable tide;
It skreened the sky, it clawed the deep,
It spattered grit on every side.

He swung his brace, he choffed the gust;
The sander-bleak unknit and fled;
The whisp-grain fell like sifted dust,
The dune-horns shivered, bows unbent.

"O hush your skurry, sander-kin,
O stow your skiff, you whirry band;
Though grains may bite and breezes spin,
Brave hands can rule the drifting sand."

So mind the sweep, the skirling song;
Respect the scud, the gleam, the span;
For dune and gust dance long and strong,
And man must gait the sandwroth's plan.

The Sandwrack

Twas sandle, and the shorn-dunes played
Their slithy shims across the plain;
All swuke and slake the drift-motes made,
And the wind did wragle-grain.

"Beware the Sandwrack, my son!—the whirring, whiskered Maw;
Beware the grit-gargoyle's teeth, the blindblast's sand-scraw!"
He gript a gritbladed spear of tins and tide-torn steel,
And sallied through the parching plume where shadowed zephyrs wheel.

The Sandwrack reeled in scud and spit, a hulking sand-sage grim;
Its whisk-scorched brows of broken shell, its breath a bitter brim.
It snargled and it snuft, it spanged the air with glassy flakes,
It whiffling whorled a thousand knives from every drifting break.

He thrust and flung the gritblade bright—crunch-crack the dunes replied;
The sand-soot sang; the siltwings flamed; the storm-wrack thinned and died.
"O frabjous shove!" the desert cried; the sand-foam slumped and sped;
He bared the Sandwrack's crumbling crown and stilled its sandy head.

Twas sandle, and the shorn-dunes sighed
As hush crept over leas;
All slunt and soft the loam-motes lay, and no more scoured the breeze.

The Twangwock

Twas springling at the rubbering hour, and the flenchy bands did pry;
All twistle-sprung and loopity-bright beneath the plastic sky;
And every crink and bandlet small did wobble, stretch, and stand,
While flummoxed desks with papered keeps held fast by Rubber-band.

Beware the Twangwocket, my friend! the snick-snap coil, beware!
The slingsnap curl, the pingly purl, the sudden twang in air!
Beware the slyer Loopernook, the binder with a grin;
For once it finds your pencil stash, it snaps, it flees, and wins.

He took his looplee, vorpish-strung, and wound it round his thumb;
And off he strode through staply woods where rubber blossoms hum.
The bands did shiver, bands did sing, the clip-clip nettles swayed;
He stretched his looplee to the moon — it sang a twinkle-shade.

Out slithered forth the Twangwocket with springy, slyer eye;
It swooped and slurped and slankled up, a rubbery reply.
One twang! — one pop! — the looplee snatched the banded beast in flight;
He plucked the snapper by its curl, and tugged with all his might.

The Twangwocket unlooped and bobbed, it flung a dozen rings;
Its bouncing belly sprang and sprang, it flazzled, flinged, and flings.
With final snap and flitter-snap the coil came cleft and slack;
He held the last long rubber-loop, the Twangwock stilled its crack.

And home he went with bands in tow, past desk and drawer and strand,
And wrapped the spoils round apple cores and bundles of command.
O, heed this tale of twang and nip: keep tidy, fast, and planned —
Lest every pen and paper thin be taken by the band.
